    id: "logistique-pme-barcode",
    date: "March 18, 2026",
    title: "EAN-13 vs Code 128: Understanding the History and Logistics of Barcodes",
    intro: "Far more than just a series of vertical lines, the barcode is the foundation of global trade globalization. Discover its origins, technical standards, and how it transforms small business management.",
    content: "The history of automatic identification dates back to 1948, when two graduate students, Norman Joseph Woodland and Bernard Silver, began looking for a solution to automate supermarket inventories. Inspired by Morse code, they stretched the dots and dashes to create a system readable by a scanner. It was only in 1952 that the patent was filed, but it wasn't until June 26, 1974, that the first consumer product, a pack of Wrigley's chewing gum, was scanned in Ohio. This invention radically changed the global economy by drastically reducing manual entry time and human error.\n\nCodification is now the silent language of global trade. For an independent merchant or an SME, the choice between the EAN-13 standard and Code 128 is a decision that directly impacts the efficiency of its entire logistics. The EAN-13 format (International Article Number) is the mandatory standard for retail. It allows a product to be identified uniquely and universally worldwide. Its structure is strictly defined: the first digits indicate the member organization's country, followed by the company code, the item number, and finally a crucial 13th digit called the check digit or checksum. This key is calculated via a specific algorithm (modulo 10), allowing the scanner to instantly verify that the previous 12 digits were read without error.\n\nCode 128, on the other hand, is considered the Swiss Army knife of modern logistics. Unlike EAN, which is purely numeric, Code 128 is a high-density alphanumeric symbology. Developed in 1981, it can encode all 128 ASCII characters. For a company that manufactures its own products or manages a warehouse, Code 128 is ideal because it allows for storing variable data such as serial numbers, expiration dates, or specific shelf location codes. Its ability to compress numeric data makes it one of the most compact and reliable formats, complying with international standards ISO/IEC 15417.\n\nWhat does adopting these standards actually simplify for an entrepreneur? First, inventory accuracy. Where manual entry generates an average of one error every 300 characters typed, barcoding reduces this risk to one error per several million scans. Second, supply chain visibility. A product scanned at every stage (receipt, storage, sale) allows for real-time stock tracking, thus avoiding stockouts or costly overstocking. Finally, point-of-sale efficiency is multiplied. Faster checkout improves the customer experience and allows for processing a much higher volume of transactions.\n\nTo ensure optimal performance, several technical details must not be overlooked when creating your labels. The most common mistake is neglecting the Quiet Zone. This is the mandatory white space to the left and right of the bars. Without this space, the scanner's laser beam cannot identify the boundaries of the code, causing frustrating reading failures. Print resolution is also a critical factor. We recommend using thermal printers with a resolution of at least 300 DPI. Inkjet printing on overly absorbent paper can cause ink bleed, altering the width of the bars and making the code non-compliant with optical reading standards.\n\nBy mastering these technical and historical fundamentals, professionals can transform a simple administrative constraint into a true growth lever. Automatic identification is not just a tool for mass retail; it is the indispensable partner for precision and responsiveness in any modern Small Business."
